culator (Nisab-based) PAGEREF _Toc235115873 \h 14 24. Islamic Inheritance (Faraid) Share Calculator PAGEREF _Toc235115874 \h 14 25. Pakistan Salary Income Tax Calculator (FBR slabs) PAGEREF _Toc235115875 \h 15 26. Electricity Bill Slab Estimator PAGEREF _Toc235115876 \h 15 27. Provident Fund / Gratuity / EOBI Calculator PAGEREF _Toc235115877 \h 16 28. Vehicle Token Tax Calculator by Province PAGEREF _Toc235115878 \h 16 29. Property Unit Converter — Marla / Kanal / Sq ft / Sq yd / Acre PAGEREF _Toc235115879 \h 16 30. Urdu-Aware Word &amp; Character Counter PAGEREF _Toc235115880 \h 17 34. Import/Customs Duty Estimator PAGEREF _Toc235115881 \h 17 35. Fabric/Cloth Requirement Calculator PAGEREF _Toc235115882 \h 18 37. Currency Devaluation / Savings Erosion Calculator PAGEREF _Toc235115883 \h 18 39. Overtime Pay Calculator (Pakistan labor law rates) PAGEREF _Toc235115884 \h 19 41. Wedding Guest Budget Calculator PAGEREF _Toc235115885 \h 19 42. Qurbani (Eid al-Adha) Cost-Split Calculator PAGEREF _Toc235115886 \h 19 43. BNPL (Buy Now Pay Later) True-Cost Calculator PAGEREF _Toc235115887 \h 20 44. Daily Wage to Monthly Equivalent Calculator PAGEREF _Toc235115888 \h 20 Category 6 — Phase-2/3 Stretch Tools PAGEREF _Toc235115889 \h 21 31. Warranty &amp; Return-Window Tracker PAGEREF _Toc235115890 \h 21 32. Flight Layover Buffer Checker PAGEREF _Toc235115891 \h 21 33. Rent vs Buy Break-Even Calculator PAGEREF _Toc235115892 \h 22 38. Tuition/School Fee Refund Proration Calculator PAGEREF _Toc235115893 \h 22 Introduction This document contains the complete and structured specifications for all 44 tools within the Draftivia application. It outlines the purpose, input fields, calculation logic, expected output format, UI component requirements, and SEO/content recommendations for each tool. The tools are grouped by category to match the layout and organization of the Draftivia platform. Use this document as the single source of truth for developing, testing, and optimizing each utility. Category 1 — Money, Freelance &amp; Work Life This section covers the specifications for all tools belonging to the category: Category 1 — Money, Freelance &amp; Work Life. 1. True Hourly Rate Calculator Keyword: true hourly rate calculator freelancer | Difficulty: Easy | Phase: Phase 1 Purpose: Helps freelancers and contractors work out the hourly rate they actually need to charge to hit a target take-home income, once unpaid admin time, unbillable hours, business costs, and time off are accounted for. Logic: Total hours worked per year = weeks × (billable hours + unpaid hours). Required gross income = (desired take-home + annual expenses) ÷ (1 − tax buffer %). True hourly rate = required gross income ÷ (weeks × billable hours per week). Expected Output: A large headline figure — "You need to charge $X/hour" — plus a breakdown table (required gross income, effective rate including unpaid time) and an optional comparison against a rate the user is currently charging. SEO &amp; Content Guidance: Explain why unpaid time changes the real rate, one worked example, an FAQ block (what counts as unpaid time, how many working weeks to assume, how the tax buffer works). Inputs: Desired annual take-home income — number, currency, Working weeks per year — number, default 48, Billable hours per week — number, Unpaid hours per week (admin, pitching, unbilled work) — number, Estimated annual business expenses — number, Tax / savings buffer — percentage, default 25% Components: Currency-aware number inputs, Stepper/slider for weeks and hours, Results card with headline number, Breakdown table, Copy-result-as-text button 2. Subscription Creep Tracker Keyword: subscription cost calculator total spend | Difficulty: Easy | Phase: Phase 1 Purpose: Lets a user list every subscription once and see total monthly and yearly spend, reframed into relatable comparisons instead of a bare sum. Logic: Normalize every row to a monthly cost (yearly ÷ 12, weekly × 4.33). Sum for total monthly and annual spend. Generate a reframing sentence, e.g. monthly total ÷ a configurable average-coffee-price constant, and — if income was entered — spend as a percentage of annual take-home. Expected Output: Total monthly and yearly spend, a breakdown list sorted highest-to-lowest, and one or two relatable comparison sentences. SEO &amp; Content Guidance: Explain why the reframing matters more than the raw total, one worked example, FAQ. Inputs: Repeatable row: subscription name (text), amount (number), billing cycle (dropdown: weekly / monthly / yearly), Optional: annual income, used only for the reframing sentence Components: Dynamic add/remove row form, Running-total sidebar, Simple bar/pie breakdown (CSS bars are enough, no heavy chart library needed), Optional localStorage save so a returning visitor doesn't retype their list 3. Meeting Cost Calculator Keyword: meeting cost calculator | Difficulty: Easy | Phase: Phase 1 Purpose: Shows the real dollar cost of a meeting from attendee count, average salary, and duration, with a shareable result card built for LinkedIn. Logic: Hourly rate per attendee = annual salary ÷ (52 × 40). Meeting cost = attendees × hourly rate × (duration ÷ 60). If recurrence is set, multiply by the occurrences per year to show a projected annual cost. Expected Output: A prominent cost figure, a secondary "if this happens weekly, that's $X/year" stat, and a downloadable/shareable image card. SEO &amp; Content Guidance: Explanation, worked example, FAQ. The share-card generator is the differentiator here — treat it as a required feature, not a nice-to-have. Inputs: Number of attendees — number, Average annual salary per attendee, or a hourly-rate toggle — number, Meeting duration — minutes, Optional: recurrence (weekly / monthly) to project annual cost Components: Number inputs with live-updating result, Canvas-based share-card generator (renders the result as a PNG), Download / copy-image button 4. Raise / Promotion Real-Impact Calculator Keyword: raise calculator real take home pay | Difficulty: Medium | Phase: Phase 2 Purpose: Shows what a percentage or dollar raise actually changes in monthly take-home pay after a simplified tax estimate, instead of just showing the raw percentage. Logic: Apply the selected slab table to both the old and new salary to get take-home pay for each. Report the delta in monthly take-home pay, not just the gross percentage change. Expected Output: Before/after comparison table plus a highlighted monthly take-home increase figure. SEO &amp; Content Guidance: Explain why gross % is misleading, worked example, FAQ, and a visible disclaimer that this is a simplified estimate, not tax advice. Inputs: Current annual salary — number, Raise type — toggle: percentage or fixed amount, Raise amount — number, Tax region — dropdown (reuse the Pakistan FBR slab data file from tool #25; ship a flat-rate generic fallback for other regions) Components: Toggle switch (% vs fixed), Region dropdown, Before/after comparison table, Simple before/after bar chart 5. Debt Payoff Visualizer — Snowball vs Avalanche Keyword: debt snowball vs avalanche calculator | Difficulty: Medium | Phase: Phase 2 Purpose: Lets a user enter multiple debts and an extra monthly payment, then compares the Snowball (smallest balance first) and Avalanche (highest interest first) payoff strategies side by side. Logic: Simulate month-by-month amortization under both orderings. Each month, allocate the extra payment to the strategy's target debt; once a debt is cleared, roll its freed-up payment into the next target debt. Track months-to-debt-free and total interest paid for each strategy. Expected Output: Side-by-side summary cards (months to payoff, total interest paid) plus a payoff-order list and a timeline chart per strategy. SEO &amp; Content Guidance: Explain both methods in plain language, worked example, FAQ. Inputs: Repeatable debt row: name, balance, interest rate %, minimum payment, Extra monthly payment available — number Components: Dynamic debt-row form, Two comparison summary cards, Line or stacked-bar chart comparing the two payoff timelines 6. Cost-Per-Use Decision Calculator Keyword: cost per use calculator | Difficulty: Easy | Phase: Phase 1 Purpose: Divides a purchase price by expected number of uses to give a true cost-per-use, to help decide whether something is worth buying. Logic: Cost per use = price ÷ expected uses. If a second item is entered, compare the two cost-per-use figures directly. Expected Output: The cost-per-use figure, and a comparison verdict sentence when a second item is entered. SEO &amp; Content Guidance: Explanation, worked example, FAQ. Inputs: Item price — number, Expected number of uses — number, Optional second item (same two fields) for a direct comparison Components: Small 2–3 field form, Optional second-item toggle, Result card 7. Commute Cost &amp; Time Reality Check Keyword: commute cost calculator | Difficulty: Easy | Phase: Phase 2 Purpose: Computes the true monthly and annual cost — and time cost — of a commute from distance, fuel or fare cost, parking, and time per trip. Logic: Monthly cost = (fuel or fare cost per trip + parking per day) × trips per week × ~4.33 weeks/month. Annual hours spent commuting = time per trip × trips per week × 52 ÷ 60, reframed into a relatable unit such as full days per year. Expected Output: Monthly $ cost, annual $ cost, and annual hours reframed (e.g. "X full days a year"). SEO &amp; Content Guidance: Explanation tied to return-to-office relevance, worked example, FAQ. Inputs: One-way distance — km or miles (unit toggle), Round trips per week — number, Fuel price per liter /gallon and vehicle fuel efficiency, OR a flat transit fare — mode toggle, Parking cost per day — optional number, One-way commute time — minutes Components: Unit toggle (km/mi, currency), Mode toggle (drive vs transit), Result cards, Breakdown table 36. Freelance Late-Payment Interest Calculator Keyword: late payment interest calculator invoice | Difficulty: Easy | Phase: Phase 2 Purpose: Calculates the interest or penalty a freelancer can fairly charge on an overdue invoice. Logic: Days late = payment date − due date. Interest owed = invoice amount × (annual rate ÷ 365) × days late. Expected Output: Interest owed, total amount now due (invoice + interest), and a suggested line of wording for an invoice reminder email. SEO &amp; Content Guidance: Explanation, worked example, FAQ. Inputs: Invoice amount — number, Due date — date, Payment/today's date — date, Annual interest rate % — number, user-editable default, Accrual method — simple daily accrual Components: Date pickers, Number inputs, Result card, Copy-suggested-wording button 40. Used-Item Fair Resale Price Estimator Keyword: fair resale price calculator used items | Difficulty: Medium | Phase: Phase 2 Purpose: Estimates a fair asking price for a used item from its original price, age, and a category-based depreciation curve. Logic: Maintain a per-category annual depreciation-rate table (data file — e.g. phones/laptops ~30–40%/yr, appliances ~15%/yr, furniture ~10%/yr), apply it compounding by age in years, then apply a condition multiplier (roughly −10% to −30%) on top. Expected Output: An estimated fair resale price range (low–high), not a single number. SEO &amp; Content Guidance: Explain the depreciation table used, worked example, FAQ, and a disclaimer that this is an estimate. Inputs: Category — dropdown: phones/laptops, appliances, furniture, other electronics, Original price — number, Age in months — number, Condition — dropdown: like new / good / fair / poor Components: Category dropdown, Number input, Condition dropdown, Result range card Category 2 — Time, Focus &amp; Remote-Work Life This section covers the specifications for all tools belonging to the category: Category 2 — Time, Focus &amp; Remote-Work Life. 8. Fair Meeting Time Rotator Keyword: timezone meeting rotation fairness | Difficulty: Medium | Phase: Phase 2 Purpose: For a recurring cross- timezone meeting, generates a rotating schedule so no single team is always stuck with the inconvenient slot. Logic: For each candidate slot, score how many participants it falls within reasonable hours for (e.g. 8am–6pm local). Rotate through the candidate slots across the upcoming occurrences, tracking a cumulative "inconvenience score" per team and choosing the rotation order that minimizes the maximum cumulative score across teams. Expected Output: A table of upcoming occurrence dates with the assigned time slot converted into each team's local time, plus a fairness-score summary. SEO &amp; Content Guidance: Explanation, worked example, FAQ. Inputs: Repeatable row: team/location name, timezone , Number of upcoming occurrences to schedule, 2–3 candidate local meeting times Components: Repeatable timezone -row form, Timezone conversion via the browser's Intl API, Schedule output table, Optional . ics calendar export 9. Async Reply-Time Expectation Generator Keyword: email signature reply time generator | Difficulty: Easy | Phase: Phase 2 Purpose: Generates a ready-to-paste "expect a reply within X" line for an email signature or Slack status, based on work hours, timezone , and days off. Logic: Template-string generation that combines the inputs into a natural sentence, with wording that adjusts for messages received outside work hours. Expected Output: A generated text block with a copy button, offered in a formal and a casual variant. SEO &amp; Content Guidance: Explanation, worked example, FAQ. Inputs: Work days — checkboxes Mon–Sun, Work hours — start/end time, Timezone — dropdown, Typical reply window — dropdown: a few hours / 1 business day / 48 hours Components: Small form, Live preview text, Copy-to-clipboard button 10. Screen Time Cost Converter Keyword: screen time cost calculator | Difficulty: Easy | Phase: Phase 1 Purpose: Converts daily screen time into a money-equivalent (based on the user's own hourly rate) and into lifetime hours, to make abstract time feel concrete. Logic: Money-equivalent = screen hours × hourly rate, shown daily/weekly/yearly. Lifetime hours if the habit continues = daily hours × 365 × remaining years. Expected Output: Daily/weekly/yearly $ equivalent, lifetime hours remaining at the current rate, and a shareable stat card. SEO &amp; Content Guidance: Explanation, worked example, FAQ. Keep the tone motivational, not preachy or shaming. Inputs: Daily screen time — hours/minutes, Hourly rate, or annual salary to derive it, Current age — number, Life-expectancy assumption — number, editable default Components: Number inputs, Result cards, Canvas-based share/download image (same pattern as the Meeting Cost Calculator) 11. Focus Session Value Ticker Keyword: focus timer value calculator | Difficulty: Easy | Phase: Phase 3 Purpose: A live-running counter during a work session that shows cumulative "value generated" in real time, based on the user's hourly rate, alongside a basic timer. Logic: A JS interval updates elapsed time each second. Value generated = (elapsed seconds ÷ 3600) × hourly rate, recalculated live. Expected Output: A live timer display with a live-increasing $ value, pause/resume/reset controls, and an optional end-of-session notification. SEO &amp; Content Guidance: Explanation, worked example, FAQ. Inputs: Hourly rate — number, Session length in minutes, or open-ended stopwatch mode, Start / pause / reset controls Components: setInterval -based live counter, Start/pause/reset buttons, Progress ring or bar, Optional browser notification (permission-gated) 12. Life-in-Weeks Visualizer Keyword: life in weeks calculator | Difficulty: Easy | Phase: Phase 3 Purpose: Turns a birthdate and a life-expectancy assumption into a grid visualization of weeks lived versus weeks remaining, computed and rendered entirely in the browser. Logic: Total weeks = years × 52.18. Weeks lived = (today − birthdate) ÷ 7 days. Weeks remaining = total − lived. Expected Output: A grid of small shaded cells (lived vs remaining), weeks-lived and weeks-remaining counts, and optional decade markers. SEO &amp; Content Guidance: Explanation with a motivational framing (not morbid), FAQ, and an explicit on-page privacy note that nothing is saved or transmitted. Inputs: Birthdate — date picker, Life-expectancy assumption — number, default ~80, clearly labeled as just a planning assumption Components: Date picker, Canvas-rendered grid (not one DOM element per cell — thousands of cells need canvas for performance), No backend calls and no data persistence — this must be stated explicitly in the UI Category 3 — Everyday Practical Calculators This section covers the specifications for all tools belonging to the category: Category 3 — Everyday Practical Calculators. 13. Itemized Bill Splitter Keyword: itemized bill splitter by what each person ordered | Difficulty: Medium | Phase: Phase 1 Purpose: Splits a restaurant bill by exactly which items each person ordered, rather than an even split, then distributes shared tax and tip proportionally to each person's subtotal. Logic: Each item's cost is split evenly among its assignees. Each person's subtotal = sum of their assigned item shares. Tax and tip are distributed proportionally: a person's share of tax/tip = (their subtotal ÷ total subtotal) × total tax/tip. Expected Output: A per-person total-owed breakdown table, with a grand-total reconciliation check. SEO &amp; Content Guidance: Explanation, worked example, FAQ. This is the most state-heavy Phase 1 build — the item-to-people relationship is many-to-many, so plan the data model before writing UI. Inputs: People list — add/remove names, Repeatable item row: item name, price, assigned to (multi-select of people, for shared items), Tax — amount or percentage, Tip — amount or percentage Components: Dynamic item rows with a multi-select (checkbox) assignment to people, People chip management (add/remove), Live-updating per-person totals table 14. Paint &amp; Wallpaper Estimator Keyword: how much paint do i need calculator | Difficulty: Easy | Phase: Phase 3 Purpose: Estimates cans of paint or rolls of wallpaper needed from room dimensions and door/window count, including a waste buffer. Logic: Wall area = perimeter × height − (doors × standard door area + windows × standard window area). Paint needed = wall area × coats ÷ coverage per can × (1 + waste), rounded up to whole cans/rolls. Expected Output: Cans/rolls needed, total wall area, and an optional cost estimate if a price-per-can is entered. SEO &amp; Content Guidance: Explanation, worked example, FAQ. Inputs: Room length, width, height, Number of doors, Number of windows, Number of coats, Coverage per can/roll — editable default, Waste buffer % — default 10% Components: Form with sensible numeric defaults, Result card 15. Recipe Scaler with Pan-Size &amp; Time Adjustment Keyword: recipe scaler pan size calculator | Difficulty: Medium | Phase: Phase 3 Purpose: Scales ingredient quantities for a different serving size or pan size, and also adjusts bake time/temperature guidance for the new pan — not ingredient math alone. Logic: Scale factor = target pan area ÷ original pan area (or target servings ÷ original servings). Ingredients scale by that factor. For time/temperature: apply a rule-of-thumb adjustment table (e.g. larger pan/shallower batter → lower temp ~15°C/25°F and increase time; smaller/deeper → the reverse) rather than exact heat-transfer physics. Expected Output: Scaled ingredient list, an adjusted bake-time range and temperature suggestion, and a caveat about checking doneness visually. SEO &amp; Content Guidance: Explanation, worked example, FAQ, and a clear disclaimer that time/temperature adjustments are an approximation, since ovens vary. Inputs: Original servings or pan size — dropdown of common pan shapes/sizes with a bundled area lookup, Target servings or pan size, Repeatable ingredient row: name, amount, unit, Original bake time and temperature Components: Repeatable ingredient rows, Pan-size lookup dropdown with bundled common tin dimensions, Result list 16. Leftover / Fridge Food-Safety Countdown Keyword: how long is leftover food good for calculator | Difficulty: Easy | Phase: Phase 3 Purpose: Turns food type plus the date cooked or opened into a countdown to the recommended use-by date, based on standard food-safety shelf-life guidance. Logic: Look up the safe-storage days for the chosen category and storage type. Use-by date = date cooked/opened + safe-storage days. Countdown = use-by date − today. Expected Output: A countdown message ("safe for 2 more days" / "use today" / "past the safe window, discard"), the use-by date, and a short storage tip. SEO &amp; Content Guidance: Explanation with a note on the general food-safety guidance the table is based on, worked example, FAQ, and a disclaimer that this isn't medical advice. Inputs: Food category — dropdown (cooked meat, cooked rice/pasta, dairy, opened jar/sauce, etc.) mapped to a bundled shelf-life lookup table, Date cooked/opened, Storage — fridge or freezer toggle Components: Dropdown, Date picker, Color-coded countdown display (green/yellow/red) 17. Luggage Weight Balancer Keyword: luggage weight balancer calculator | Difficulty: Easy–Medium | Phase: Phase 3 Purpose: Given the current weight of several bags, suggests how to redistribute items so every bag stays under a per-bag airline weight limit. Logic: A simple greedy balancing routine: while any bag exceeds its limit and another bag has headroom, suggest moving an amount from the over-limit bag to the under-limit bag; repeat until balanced, or flag the whole set as overweight if total weight exceeds combined capacity. Expected Output: A short list of suggested moves ("move ~2kg from Bag A to Bag B"), the projected final weight per bag, and an overall-overweight warning if applicable. SEO &amp; Content Guidance: Explanation, worked example, FAQ. Inputs: Repeatable bag row: bag name, current weight, Weight limit — single shared value, or per-bag Components: Repeatable bag rows, Limit input, Result instruction list 18. Group Gift Contribution Splitter Keyword: group gift contribution calculator | Difficulty: Easy | Phase: Phase 3 Purpose: Total gift cost and number of contributors produces a suggested split, with an optional uneven/weighted-contribution mode. Logic: Even mode: per-person amount = total ÷ number of contributors. Weighted mode: distribute total proportional to each contributor's weight, adjusting the last contributor's share by a rounding remainder so totals reconcile exactly. Expected Output: A per-person amount-owed table with a running-total check. SEO &amp; Content Guidance: Explanation, worked example, FAQ. Inputs: Total gift cost — number, Mode — toggle: even split / weighted split, Repeatable contributor row: name, and (if weighted) a weight or fixed amount Components: Repeatable contributor rows, Mode toggle, Result table Category 4 — Content, Social &amp; Accessibility This section covers the specifications for all tools belonging to the category: Category 4 — Content, Social &amp; Accessibility. 19. Multi-Platform Post Length Previewer Keyword: social media character count preview all platforms | Difficulty: Easy | Phase: Phase 1 Purpose: Lets a user paste text once and see live truncation previews of how it will display across X, LinkedIn, Instagram, and Threads simultaneously. Logic: Maintain a per-platform character-limit and visible-before-truncation table (e.g. X ~280 chars total; LinkedIn ~3000 total but ~210 visible before "see more"; Instagram caption 2200 total but ~125 visible; Threads 500 chars) and apply it live as the user types. Expected Output: Four side-by-side preview cards, each showing the visible text plus the truncation point, and a remaining-character count per platform. SEO &amp; Content Guidance: Explanation, worked example, FAQ. Keep the preview cards generically styled to stay clear of trademark/IP issues. Inputs: A single shared textarea for the post text Components: Single shared textarea driving four live-updating preview cards, Per-platform card styling using generic colors /layout cues only — no logos or trademarked marks 20. Alt-Text Quality Checker Keyword: alt text checker accessibility | Difficulty: Medium | Phase: Phase 3 Purpose: Scores user-entered alt text against accessibility best practices using a rule-based engine — no AI/ML involved. Logic: Rule checks: flag redundant phrases ("image of", "picture of", "graphic of"), flag length outside roughly 5–125 characters, flag ALL CAPS, flag missing end punctuation, flag keyword-stuffing (a word repeated 3+ times). Produce a 0–100 score with an itemized pass/fail list. Expected Output: A score plus an itemized checklist (pass/fail with a one-line reason for each), and rewrite guidance rather than an auto-rewrite. SEO &amp; Content Guidance: Explanation of why alt text matters, a before/after example, FAQ. Keep the rules engine self-contained client-side logic — no external dependency. Inputs: Alt text — textarea , Optional: image context/page topic, for a redundancy check Components: Textarea with live rule evaluation as the user types, Checklist UI with pass/fail icons 21. Hashtag CamelCase Formatter Keyword: hashtag capitalize each word camelcase | Difficulty: Easy | Phase: Phase 3 Purpose: Capitalizes each word within a hashtag for screen-reader accessibility (#LoveIsLove instead of #loveislove). Logic: Automatic word-boundary detection on already-concatenated lowercase text (e.g. splitting " loveislove " back into words) is not reliably solvable and should not be attempted. Build the input flow around word-separated entry instead: the user types or pastes words with spaces, and the tool joins and capitalizes them. Expected Output: Formatted hashtag(s) with a copy button, supporting a batch list (one hashtag per line). SEO &amp; Content Guidance: Explanation of the accessibility reason, worked example, FAQ. Flag the word-boundary limitation explicitly in the UI copy so users understand the input format. Inputs: Text input of hashtag word(s), entered space-separated (e.g. "love is love"), one or more per line for batch mode Components: Textarea /input, Copy-to-clipboard, Batch list output 22. Password Weakness Explainer Keyword: why is my password weak checker | Difficulty: Medium | Phase: Phase 3 Purpose: Explains specifically why a password is weak — dictionary word, keyboard-walk pattern, common substitution, sequential characters — instead of a generic strength bar. Logic: Must run 100% client-side; the password value must never be transmitted over the network or captured by any analytics/logging script. Check against: a small bundled common-password wordlist, keyboard-walk patterns (qwerty, asdf , 12345-style sequences), leetspeak substitution before a dictionary check (a→@, e→3, etc.), repeated-character runs, sequential numeric/alphabetic runs, and length thresholds. Expected Output: An itemized list of specific weaknesses found (or a plainly-worded "no obvious pattern weaknesses detected" — never a "strong/safe" verdict, since this only checks patterns, not full entropy). SEO &amp; Content Guidance: Explanation, worked example, FAQ, and a prominent privacy note ("this never leaves your browser") plus a disclaimer that passing these checks doesn't guarantee security. Critical build constraint: verify zero network calls carry the typed password, including via analytics scripts. Inputs: Password — masked input field with a show/hide toggle Components: Password input with show/hide toggle, Live rule evaluation, Itemized results list Category 5 — Pakistan / South Asia This section covers the specifications for all tools belonging to the category: Category 5 — Pakistan / South Asia. 23. Zakat Calculator ( Nisab -based) Keyword: zakat calculator pakistan nisab gold silver | Difficulty: Easy–Medium | Phase: Phase 1 Purpose: Calculates Zakat due from the gold/silver Nisab threshold, using user-entered current gold/silver rates since the site has no live pricing backend. Logic: Nisab threshold = value of 87.48g gold or 612.36g silver at the entered rates (the lower of the two, per common practice). Total zakatable wealth = cash + gold value + silver value + business inventory + receivables − debts. If total ≥ Nisab , Zakat due = total × 2.5%. Expected Output: The Nisab threshold value, total zakatable wealth, and Zakat due (or a clear "below Nisab , no Zakat due" message). SEO &amp; Content Guidance: Explain Nisab and the 2.5% rule, a worked example, FAQ, a clear note that gold/silver rates must be entered by the user against a current source, and a disclaimer that this is a general calculation, not a substitute for a scholar's guidance on complex cases. Expect a seasonal traffic spike around Ramadan. Inputs: Cash and bank balances, Gold owned — grams, by karat if possible, Silver owned — grams, Business inventory value, Receivables owed to the user, minus debts owed by the user, Current gold price per gram — user-entered, with a helper note to check a current source, Current silver price per gram — user-entered, same note Components: Multi-field form grouped by asset type, Result card with a breakdown table 24. Islamic Inheritance ( Faraid ) Share Calculator Keyword: islamic inheritance calculator faraid shares | Difficulty: Hard | Phase: Phase 2 Purpose: Rule-based calculation of inheritance shares among surviving heirs, following Faraid rules. Logic: Implement the standard Faraid share-priority rules: fixed shares (Fard) for entitled heirs, followed by residuary (Asaba) distribution of any remainder, applied according to the specific combination of surviving heirs entered. Expected Output: A per-heir share, shown as both a fraction and a currency amount. SEO &amp; Content Guidance: Explanation, worked example, FAQ, and a prominent disclaimer that results are a general estimate and complex estates should be reviewed with a qualified scholar. BUILD HOLD POINT: this is the single highest accuracy-risk tool on the site — do not publish the rule set until it has been checked against a reliable fiqh source by someone qualified. Treat this as a release gate, not a normal QA pass. Inputs: Estate value after debts/funeral costs/bequests are deducted, Structured entry for each possible heir category (spouse, sons, daughters, father, mother, and the rest of the standard Faraid heir list) Components: Structured, grouped form for heir entry (a wizard-style flow is reasonable given the number of fields), Results table by heir 25. Pakistan Salary Income Tax Calculator (FBR slabs) Keyword: pakistan salary tax calculator fbr | Difficulty: Easy | Phase: Phase 1 Purpose: Computes income tax due on salary using the current FBR slab rates for the applicable fiscal year. Logic: Maintain the slab-rate table as a separate, easily-editable JSON data file rather than inline code. Apply progressive slab calculation: tax = sum of (portion of income falling in each bracket × that bracket's rate). Expected Output: Total annual tax, monthly tax, effective tax rate %, and net take-home salary. SEO &amp; Content Guidance: Explanation, worked example, FAQ, a visible "slabs current as of [tax year]" note, and a disclaimer that this isn't tax advice. Maintenance note for the build agent: Pakistan's tax year starts July 1 — this data file needs to be reviewed and updated every fiscal year. Inputs: Annual or monthly taxable salary — with a toggle, Fiscal year — dropdown if recent slabs differ, Filer/non-filer status, if it affects the applicable rate Components: Form with a monthly/annual toggle, Result table breaking down tax owed per slab 26. Electricity Bill Slab Estimator Keyword: electricity bill calculator pakistan units | Difficulty: Medium | Phase: Phase 1 Purpose: Estimates an electricity bill from units (kWh) consumed, using Pakistan's tiered tariff slab structure. Logic: Maintain the tiered slab-rate table as a data file, applied progressively like a tax bracket calculation, plus configurable line items for standard additional charges (fuel price adjustment, GST, TV license fee) so the estimate tracks reasonably close to a real bill. Expected Output: An estimated bill broken down by slab and surcharge line items, plus a total. SEO &amp; Content Guidance: Explanation, worked example, FAQ, a disclaimer that the actual bill may vary by DISCO and adjustment, and a maintenance note that the tariff table needs periodic updates as a data file. Inputs: Units consumed — kWh, Consumer category — residential/commercial, Region/DISCO, if rates differ, Protected/non-protected category, if applicable Components: Form, Breakdown table 27. Provident Fund / Gratuity / EOBI Calculator Keyword: gratuity calculator pakistan provident fund eobi | Difficulty: Medium | Phase: Phase 2 Purpose: Estimates end-of-service benefits for salaried employees: provident fund accumulation, gratuity, and a rough EOBI pension estimate. Logic: PF ≈ (employee % + employer %) × basic salary × months of service, with an optional interest-rate field for compounding. Gratuity uses a configurable formula (commonly last basic salary ÷ 30 or ÷ 26 × years × a factor). EOBI is presented as a rough estimate only, tied to a configurable minimum-pension constant that should be periodically updated. Expected Output: Three clearly separate estimated totals — PF, Gratuity, EOBI — each labeled as an estimate, not a guarantee. SEO &amp; Content Guidance: Explanation, worked example, FAQ, and a disclaimer to confirm actual figures with HR or EOBI directly. Inputs: Basic monthly salary, Years of service, Employee and employer PF contribution % — editable defaults, EOBI contribution status — yes/no, Gratuity formula basis — a configurable constant, since employer policy varies Components: Form grouped by benefit type, Result cards 28. Vehicle Token Tax Calculator by Province Keyword: vehicle token tax calculator punjab sindh kpk balochistan | Difficulty: Medium | Phase: Phase 2 Purpose: A single calculator covering token tax rates across Punjab, Sindh, KPK, and Balochistan for a given vehicle. Logic: A per-province rate-lookup data file, keyed by vehicle type, engine-capacity bracket, and age bracket where applicable. Expected Output: The estimated token tax due. SEO &amp; Content Guidance: Explanation, worked example, FAQ, a disclaimer that rates change and should be confirmed with the provincial excise department, and a maintenance note that the rate table needs periodic verification. Inputs: Province — dropdown, Vehicle type — car/motorcycle/etc., Engine capacity — cc, Vehicle age, where a province's rate varies by it Components: Form with province and vehicle-type dropdowns, Result card 29. Property Unit Converter — Marla / Kanal / Sq ft / Sq yd / Acre Keyword: marla to square feet kanal converter | Difficulty: Easy | Phase: Phase 1 Purpose: Bidirectional conversion between South Asian property units (Marla, Kanal) and standard units (sq ft, sq yd, acre, sq m). Logic: A fixed conversion-factor table relative to a base unit (sq ft). Use the Punjab/Pakistan-standard definition as the default: 1 Marla = 225 sq ft, 1 Kanal = 20 Marla = 4500 sq ft. Getting this specific definition right is the whole point of the tool — do not substitute a different regional Marla value without a clearly labeled toggle. Expected Output: The converted value, plus a static quick-reference conversion table shown below the calculator. SEO &amp; Content Guidance: Explanation, worked example, FAQ. Inputs: Amount — number, From-unit — dropdown (Marla, Kanal, Sq ft, Sq yd, Acre, Sq m, Sq km, Hectare), To-unit — dropdown, same list Components: Two unit dropdowns plus an amount input, Instant bidirectional conversion, Static reference table 30. Urdu-Aware Word &amp; Character Counter Keyword: urdu word counter character count | Difficulty: Medium | Phase: Phase 2 Purpose: Correctly counts words and characters in Urdu script text, handling Unicode grapheme clusters properly, which most generic counters get wrong. Logic: Use proper Unicode grapheme-cluster segmentation — the JS Intl.Segmenter API with granularity 'grapheme' and 'word' — rather than naive .length or space-splitting, since Urdu/Arabic-script combining marks and ligatures break naive counting. Expected Output: Live word count, grapheme-correct character count, and character count excluding spaces. SEO &amp; Content Guidance: Explanation of why this differs from generic counters, worked example, FAQ. The Intl.Segmenter /RTL handling is the actual differentiator — flag it clearly as a hard requirement, not an optional nicety. Inputs: Textarea for Urdu or mixed Urdu/English text Components: Textarea with live counters, Right-to-left text direction support in the textarea styling 34. Import/Customs Duty Estimator Keyword: customs duty calculator pakistan online order | Difficulty: Medium | Phase: Phase 1 Purpose: Estimates customs duty and sales tax owed on an international parcel or online order landing in Pakistan. Logic: A simplified approximation, not an exact HS-code engine: duty = (value + shipping) × category duty rate (from the lookup table), plus sales tax % applied to the duty-inclusive value. Expected Output: Estimated duty plus tax total, and total landed cost (item + shipping + duty + tax). SEO &amp; Content Guidance: Explanation, worked example, FAQ, a prominent disclaimer that actual customs assessment can vary by exact HS code and officer discretion, and a maintenance note that the category rate table should be a separate, updatable data file. Inputs: Item category — dropdown mapped to a duty-rate lookup table, Declared value, Shipping cost, Currency, converted to PKR via a user-entered exchange rate (no live FX backend) Components: Form with category dropdown and a currency-conversion field, Result breakdown 35. Fabric/Cloth Requirement Calculator Keyword: fabric yardage calculator shalwar kameez suit | Difficulty: Easy | Phase: Phase 2 Purpose: Estimates yardage or meters of fabric needed for a stitched outfit from height and garment style. Logic: A per-garment-style lookup/formula table (data file) mapping height bracket and fabric width to required yardage, using standard tailoring rules of thumb. Expected Output: Estimated yardage/meters needed, with a note on the fabric-width assumption used. SEO &amp; Content Guidance: Explanation, worked example, FAQ, and a disclaimer that a tailor's exact requirement can vary by design and print-matching. Inputs: Height — cm or inches, Garment style — dropdown (shalwar kameez, 2-piece suit, 3-piece suit, kurta, etc.), Sleeve style, where relevant, Fabric width — this materially changes the answer and must be an input, not assumed Components: Form, Result card 37. Currency Devaluation / Savings Erosion Calculator Keyword: pkr devaluation calculator savings loss inflation | Difficulty: Easy | Phase: Phase 1 Purpose: Shows how PKR savings have lost purchasing power against USD, or against inflation, over a chosen period, in relatable terms. Logic: vs USD mode: compare the USD value of the amount at the start rate against what it converts to at the end rate, expressed as a % purchasing-power change. vs inflation mode: real value = amount ÷ (1 + inflation)^ years, expressed as erosion in today's-PKR terms. Expected Output: Purchasing power lost (% and PKR-equivalent), a relatable reframing sentence, and — if a small bundled historical-rate dataset is included — an optional trend chart. SEO &amp; Content Guidance: Explanation, worked example, FAQ, and a clear note on the data source/assumptions used — if a historical dataset is bundled, label it "as of [date], update periodically." Inputs: Amount saved, Start date and end date, Comparison mode — toggle: vs USD exchange rate / vs inflation rate, Start and end exchange or inflation rate — user-entered Components: Form with a mode toggle, Result card, Optional line chart if historical data is bundled 39. Overtime Pay Calculator (Pakistan labor law rates) Keyword: overtime pay calculator pakistan labor law | Difficulty: Medium | Phase: Phase 2 Purpose: Computes overtime pay owed from base wage and hours worked, using Pakistan's legally mandated overtime multiplier. Logic: Hourly rate = monthly salary ÷ (standard weekly hours × ~4.33). Overtime hours = actual hours − standard hours. Overtime pay = overtime hours × hourly rate × the applicable multiplier (commonly 2×, from a lookup table by law basis). Expected Output: Overtime hours, overtime pay owed, and total pay (base + overtime). SEO &amp; Content Guidance: Explanation, worked example, FAQ, and a disclaimer that rules vary by sector/province and this is a general estimate. Inputs: Base monthly salary or hourly wage, Standard working hours per week — default per the applicable law, Actual hours worked, Sector/law basis — dropdown, since the multiplier can differ (e.g. Factories Act vs Shops &amp; Establishment ordinances) Components: Form, Result breakdown 41. Wedding Guest Budget Calculator Keyword: wedding budget calculator per guest pakistan | Difficulty: Easy | Phase: Phase 1 Purpose: Total budget, guest count, and per-head catering cost show what's realistically affordable, split across the major budget categories. Logic: Catering total = guests × per-head cost, subtracted from the total budget first since it scales predictably. The remaining budget is distributed across the other categories per the (auto-normalized to 100%) weight percentages. Expected Output: A per-category budget breakdown table/chart, plus a remaining-or-overspend warning if catering alone exceeds the total budget. SEO &amp; Content Guidance: Explanation, worked example, FAQ. Inputs: Total budget, Guest count, Per-head catering cost estimate, Category weight sliders — catering, venue, décor, photography, clothing, misc — default preset %, user-adjustable Components: Form with sliders that auto-normalize to sum 100%, Result breakdown table or chart 42. Qurbani (Eid al-Adha) Cost-Split Calculator Keyword: qurbani cost split calculator shares | Difficulty: Easy | Phase: Phase 1 Purpose: Splits the cost of a sacrificial animal fairly across multiple family or group shares, respecting the standard limit on shares per animal. Logic: Validate that the number of shares does not exceed the maximum allowed for the chosen animal type (1 for goat/sheep, 7 for cattle/buffalo/camel). Per-person cost = total cost ÷ number of shares. Expected Output: Per-person amount owed, and a clear validation warning if the share count exceeds the allowed maximum for that animal. SEO &amp; Content Guidance: Explain the 7-share rule, worked example, FAQ. Getting the share-limit validation right is the whole point of this tool — treat it as a required check, not a soft warning. Inputs: Animal type — dropdown: goat/sheep (1 share only, not divisible) vs cow/buffalo/camel (up to 7 shares), Total animal cost, Number of people sharing Components: Dropdown, Number inputs, Result card with validation messaging 43. BNPL (Buy Now Pay Later) True-Cost Calculator Keyword: bnpl true cost calculator pakistan installment | Difficulty: Easy | Phase: Phase 2 Purpose: Reveals the real effective annualized cost of a BNPL/ installment plan compared to its advertised markup, so it can be compared honestly to paying cash. Logic: Markup = total payable − cash price. Effective rate = markup ÷ cash price, annualized based on the repayment period using a simplified APR-style approximation: effective annual rate = (1 + period rate)^ (365 ÷ period days) − 1, so plans of different lengths are comparable. Expected Output: Total markup in currency, effective annualized rate %, and a plain-language comparison sentence. SEO &amp; Content Guidance: Explanation, worked example, FAQ, and a disclaimer that this is a simplified approximation for comparison purposes, not a formal APR disclosure. Inputs: Cash price, Total amount payable via installments , Number of installments , Installment period — weeks or months Components: Form, Result card with the effective-rate figure prominently displayed 44. Daily Wage to Monthly Equivalent Calculator Keyword: daily wage to monthly salary calculator | Difficulty: Easy | Phase: Phase 2 Purpose: Estimates realistic monthly income for daily-wage workers, accounting for missed or no-work days rather than naively multiplying by 30. Logic: Monthly income = daily wage × (expected working days − estimated missed days). Expected Output: A realistic monthly income estimate, shown alongside the naive "daily × 30" figure for comparison. SEO &amp; Content Guidance: Explanation, worked example, FAQ. Inputs: Daily wage rate, Expected working days per month — default ~24–26, editable, Estimated missed days per month (rain, illness, no work available) Components: Simple form, Result comparison card Category 6 — Phase-2/3 Stretch Tools This section covers the specifications for all tools belonging to the category: Category 6 — Phase-2/3 Stretch Tools. 31. Warranty &amp; Return-Window Tracker Keyword: warranty return window tracker calculator | Difficulty: Easy | Phase: Phase 3 Purpose: Purchase date plus store policy days gives a countdown to warranty/return-window expiry, with an optional reminder. Logic: Return deadline = purchase date + return-window days. Warranty deadline = purchase date + warranty length. Countdown to each. Expected Output: Two countdowns (return window, warranty), color-coded by urgency. SEO &amp; Content Guidance: Explanation, worked example, FAQ. Inputs: Item name, Purchase date, Return-window days, Warranty length — days/months/years Components: Form, A list of tracked items stored client-side via localStorage (no accounts/no backend), Countdown cards 32. Flight Layover Buffer Checker Keyword: is my layover long enough calculator | Difficulty: Hard | Phase: Phase 3 Purpose: Checks whether a layover between two flights is realistically long enough, given the airports involved. Logic: Compare the entered layover duration against a bundled minimum-connection-time (MCT) reference figure for the airport/connection type, and classify the result as comfortable, tight, or risky. Expected Output: A verdict (comfortable/tight/risky) citing the MCT reference used, plus general tips if the connection is international. SEO &amp; Content Guidance: Explanation, worked example, FAQ, a clear disclaimer to always confirm with the airline, and a build note: this needs a real, sourced, periodically-updated airport MCT dataset — do not fabricate figures. If reliable sourced data can't be secured, hold this tool rather than ship guessed numbers. Inputs: Arrival airport, Connecting/departure airport, Layover duration, Terminal change needed — yes/no/unknown, Connection type — international-to-domestic or same-type Components: Airport search/autocomplete, Form, Result verdict card 33. Rent vs Buy Break-Even Calculator Keyword: rent vs buy calculator pakistan | Difficulty: Medium | Phase: Phase 3 Purpose: A simplified rent-vs-buy break-even calculation that includes the opportunity cost of the down payment, localized to Pakistan's PKR context. Logic: Compute cumulative cost of buying over N years (mortgage payments + a maintenance/tax estimate − equity built − appreciation) against cumulative cost of renting plus investing the down-payment difference at the given return rate, then find the year those two curves cross. Expected Output: The break-even year, plus a side-by-side cumulative-cost chart over time. SEO &amp; Content Guidance: Explanation, worked example, FAQ, and a disclaimer that this is simplified and excludes some real-world costs and taxes. Inputs: Home price, Down payment, Mortgage interest rate and loan term, Monthly rent for a comparable property, Expected annual home appreciation %, Expected investment return % if the down payment were invested instead Components: Form, Line chart comparing two cumulative-cost curves 38. Tuition/School Fee Refund Proration Calculator Keyword: school fee refund calculator withdrawal | Difficulty: Medium | Phase: Phase 3 Purpose: Days attended versus total term length gives an estimated refund owed on mid-term withdrawal, using a proration method the user selects to match their institution's stated policy. Logic: Straight-line: refund = fee × (remaining days ÷ total days). Monthly-block: refund = fee × (remaining whole-or-partial months owed ÷ total months), rounding up partial months per common policy wording. Expected Output: The estimated refund under the selected method, with a side-by-side figure for the other method for comparison. SEO &amp; Content Guidance: Explanation, worked example, FAQ, and a prominent disclaimer that the actual refund is governed by the specific institution's written policy, and the user should confirm directly with the school. Inputs: Total term length — days, Days attended before withdrawal, Total fee paid, Proration method — dropdown: straight-line daily proration, or monthly-block proration (any part of a month counts as a full month owed) Components: Form with a method toggle, Result comparison 